{
  "title": "CSS Grid vs Flexbox: When to Use Which",
  "description": "Understanding the differences between CSS Grid and Flexbox, and learning when to use each layout system for optimal web design.",
  "slug": "css-grid-vs-flexbox",
  "author": "Emily Rodriguez",
  "coverImage": "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507003211169-0a1dd7228f2d?w=800",
  "layout": {
    "type": "two-column",
    "maxWidth": "1000px",
    "showTableOfContents": true
  },
  "settings": {
    "enableVoting": true,
    "enableSocialShare": true,
    "enableComments": true
  },
  "tags": ["CSS", "Grid", "Flexbox", "Web Design", "Frontend"],
  "links": [
    {
      "label": "CSS Grid Guide",
      "url": "https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/complete-guide-grid/",
      "type": "external"
    },
    {
      "label": "Flexbox Guide",
      "url": "https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/",
      "type": "external"
    }
  ],
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 1,
        "text": "CSS Grid vs Flexbox"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "Both CSS Grid and Flexbox are powerful layout systems, but they serve different purposes. Understanding when to use each is crucial for modern web development."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "Flexbox: One-Dimensional Layouts"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "Flexbox is designed for one-dimensional layouts - either a row or a column. It's perfect for aligning items within a container."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": {
        "code": ".container {\n  display: flex;\n  justify-content: space-between;\n  align-items: center;\n}",
        "language": "css",
        "filename": "styles.css"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "Grid: Two-Dimensional Layouts"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "CSS Grid excels at two-dimensional layouts - both rows and columns. It's ideal for complex page layouts."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": {
        "code": ".container {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);\n  gap: 20px;\n}",
        "language": "css",
        "filename": "styles.css"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "When to Use Each"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "content": {
        "style": "ordered",
        "items": [
          "Use Flexbox for components and small-scale layouts",
          "Use Grid for page-level layouts",
          "You can combine both - Grid for the page, Flexbox for components",
          "Flexbox is better for content-driven layouts",
          "Grid is better for layout-driven designs"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "divider",
      "content": {}
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "Remember: There's no one-size-fits-all solution. Often, the best layouts use both Grid and Flexbox together."
      }
    }
  ],
  "status": "published"
}

{
  "title": "Introduction to GraphQL: A Modern API Query Language",
  "description": "Learn how GraphQL revolutionizes API design by allowing clients to request exactly the data they need, nothing more, nothing less.",
  "slug": "introduction-to-graphql",
  "author": "Alex Thompson",
  "coverImage": "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1460925895917-afdab827c52f?w=800",
  "layout": {
    "type": "single-column",
    "maxWidth": "850px",
    "showTableOfContents": true
  },
  "settings": {
    "enableVoting": true,
    "enableSocialShare": true,
    "enableComments": true
  },
  "tags": ["GraphQL", "API", "Backend", "Technology"],
  "links": [
    {
      "label": "GraphQL Official Site",
      "url": "https://graphql.org/",
      "type": "external"
    },
    {
      "label": "Apollo GraphQL",
      "url": "https://www.apollographql.com/",
      "type": "external"
    }
  ],
  "blocks": [
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 1,
        "text": "What is GraphQL?"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "GraphQL is a query language for APIs and a runtime for executing those queries. It provides a complete and understandable description of the data in your API."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "Key Benefits"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "list",
      "content": {
        "style": "unordered",
        "items": [
          "Ask for exactly what you need",
          "Get many resources in a single request",
          "Strongly typed schema",
          "Powerful developer tools",
          "Evolve your API without versions"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "Example Query"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": {
        "code": "query {\n  user(id: \"1\") {\n    name\n    email\n    posts {\n      title\n      content\n    }\n  }\n}",
        "language": "graphql",
        "filename": null
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "content": {
        "level": 2,
        "text": "GraphQL vs REST"
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": {
        "text": "While REST uses multiple endpoints for different resources, GraphQL uses a single endpoint. This allows clients to specify exactly what data they need, reducing over-fetching and under-fetching."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "content": {
        "variant": "success",
        "title": "Pro Tip",
        "content": "GraphQL is particularly useful for mobile applications where bandwidth is a concern."
      }
    }
  ],
  "status": "published"
}
